he Jewish Labor movement, and a place where Orthodoxy struggled vigorously with modernity. The two volumes of Pinsk history were originally part of a literature created by Jews who survived the Holocaust and were determined to keep in memory a vital world that flourished for half a millennium. In this case, the results are extraordinary: no town of Eastern Europe has been described in such fascinating detail, invaluable to Jewish and non-Jewish historians alike. For the second volume of this two-volume collection, see The Jews of Pinsk, 1881-1941.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aJewszBelaruszPinskxHistory. 0aJewszLithuaniaxHistory. 0aJewszPolandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aMirsky , Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMirsky, Mark Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadav, Mordechai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosman, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosman, Moshe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804783088zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804783088/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles